<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911231-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>911231-0013.</DOCID><HL>   Credit Markets:   Bond Prices Surge on Fresh Manufacturing Data   Hinting Economy Has Fallen Back Into Recession   ----   By Constance Mitchell and Kevin Donovan   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>12/31/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17</SO><IN>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)STOCK AND BOND REGISTRATIONS, PRICINGS (REG)</IN><NS>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE RATES (MOR)BOND AND STOCK REGISTRATIONS AND PRICINGS (REG)</NS><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Fresh indications that the economy has slippedback into recession triggered a rally in bonds yesterday.   The bond market's bellwether security, the 30-yearTreasury bond, rose 7/8 point, or $8.75 for a bond with a$1,000 face amount. The issue's yield, which moves in theopposite direction of its price, eased to 7.44% from 7.51% onFriday.</LP><TEXT>   The bond market opened little changed in quiet holidaytrading. But the market came to life shortly after thePurchasing Management Association of Chicago reported thatits composite index of business activity fell to 46.0% inDecember from 53.2% in November. A reading above 50%generally indicates that the manufacturing sector isexpanding, while a reading below 50% indicates a contraction.   Economists said that the Chicago index raises thepossibility that the National Association of PurchasingManagement's index of industrial health also will fall belowthe crucial 50% level. The national report is due outThursday.   &quot;This is a bad tiding for the first quarter,&quot; said DonaldFine, chief market analyst at Chase Manhattan Bank Corp.,referring to the downturn in the Chicago purchasingmanagement index. &quot;The report shows that the industrialsector is once again contracting. And that's not only truefor Chicago, I think the national number will also show thatthe industrial sector is contracting.&quot;   Slow or negative economic growth is considered bullish forbonds because it often leads to lower inflation and interestrates, trends that often result in higher bond prices.   &quot;The {bond} market is convinced that the economy won'tgrow and that the Fed will ease {monetary policy} again,&quot;says Mitchell Held, economist at Smith Barney, Harris Upham andamp;Co.   The Federal Reserve took a relatively aggressive easingstep Dec. 20, cutting the discount rate by a full percentagepoint, to 3.5%. However, although subsequent economic datahave pointed to continuing economic weakness, Mr. Held sayshe isn't &quot;so sure&quot; the economy is weak enough to prompt anyfurther easing by the central bank.   Mr. Held thinks bond market expectations of economicactivity &quot;are too low,&quot; and that small increases infourth-quarter and first-quarter gross domestic product arepossible. Although GDP grew at an annual rate of 1.8% in thethird quarter, fourth-quarter statistics have by and largeportrayed an economy contracting again.   But among the recent portents of recovery have been risingmoney supply growth, a soaring stock market and firmerhousing data. On the latter front, the National Associationof Realtors said yesterday morning that existing homes salesrose 5.4% in November to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of3,330,000.   Bond market participants ignored that news, however,confident that a stagnant economy warranted buyinglonger-term securities for their yield advantage overshort-term issues.   The market also entered uncharted technical territoryyesterday as the March Treasury bond futures contract closedat 104 8/32, a record high for a bond futures contract,according to Optima Futures Analysis Inc., Chicago.   Looking ahead, the Public Securities Association hasrecommended a 2 p.m. EST end to government securities tradingtoday ahead of the New Year holiday.   On the economic calendar, the Commerce Department isslated to release the November index of leading economicindicators at 8:30 a.m. EST this morning. A Dow Jones CapitalMarkets Report survey suggests that economists look for theindex to have declined 0.4% in November after rising 0.1% inOctober.                                                                                                          Treasury Securities                                                                                                          Treasurys ended sharply higher in light trading.   The benchmark 30-year bond ended at a price of 106 17/32to yield 7.44% compared with 105 21/32 to yield 7.51% onFriday.   Other market sectors also fared well. For example, 10-yearnotes ended at 105 15/32 to yield 6.71%, up from 104 24/32 toyield 6.81% on Friday. Two-year notes rose 1/8 to 100 14/32to yield 4.75%.   Meanwhile, the Treasury sold $10.45 billion of billsyesterday at its regular weekly auction. The average discountrate on both new three-month bills and six-month bills was3.91%. Those rates were up from last week's auction, when therate on threemonth bills was 3.75% and the rate on six-monthbills was 3.85%.   Here are the details of yesterday's auction by theTreasury of 13-week and 26-week bills:                                                                                                          Rates are determined by the difference between thepurchase price and face value. Thus, higher bidding narrowsthe investor's return while lower bidding widens it. Thepercentage rates are calculated on a 360-day year, while thecoupon-equivalent yield is based on a 366-day year.                                                                                                                                    13-Week         26-Week                                                                                                        Applications .......... $32,295,39