er comment.   Whichever choice the firm makes, &quot;bankruptcy is prettyimminent,&quot; contends Jan Dillow, senior high-yield analyst atSalomon Brothers Inc. &quot;Now it becomes a waiting game and it'sup to the bankruptcy court&quot; how the company's bonds arelikely to trade.   Zale's 13.125% senior subordinated debentures, due 2007,dropped 1/2 point to 11 1/2.   In the broader market, most junk bond prices wereunchanged, as were investment-grade corporate bonds. Therewere no new issues in the debt markets this session.   The junk bonds of Burlington Holdings Inc. continued theirrecent rise, with gains of about 1 1/2 points. Burlingtonbonds have gained since the announcement ofbetterthan-expected results for the fourth quarter, whichwere released last Friday. The textile company said it earned$8.3 million in the quarter, compared with a loss of $32.5million in the year-ago period.   Burlington's 13.875% senior subordinated notes, due 1996,gained 1 1/2 points to 91. The notes had traded at 88 beforethe earnings results were released.                                                                                                          Municipal Bonds                                                                                                          Prices of municipal bonds ended unchanged to as much as1/2 point higher.   Among seasoned issues, the Florida Board of Education's6.70% securities of 2022 finished 1/2 higher at 101 3/8 toyield 6.57%.   No large municipal bond issues were priced yesterday.   An early close of 2 p.m. EST is anticipated ahead of theNew Year's holiday, in line with other bond markets.   On next week's new issue calendar, a Goldman, Sachs andamp; Co.group is expected to price $775 million New Jersey TurnpikeAuthority revenue bonds one day during the week. Proceedswill be used for the authority's capital program, includingpurchase of a 4.4 mile portion of Interstate 95 from theState of New Jersey, for $400 million.                                                                                                          Mortgage andamp; Asset-Backed Securities                                                                                                          Prices of mortgage securities ended higher.   In thin preholiday trading, Government National MortgageAssociation 7.5% securities for January delivery rose 11/32to 100 29/32, Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. Gold 7.5%securities increased 14/32 to 99 24/32 and Federal NationalMortgage Association 7.5% securities gained 14/32 to 9920/32.   Yesterday's gains extend a rally that has made it moredifficult to find issues trading around par. Those that areavailable have been in hot demand.   The majority of the actively traded mortgage securitiescarrying prices near par are the 7.5% issues, which tend tobe in relatively short supply.   Market players now eagerly await Thursday's Freddie Macsecurities prepayment figures for the mid-November tomid-December period. Mortgage market activity is seen heatingup again after that report and the December data due out nextweek from Fannie Mae and Ginnie Mae.   If the figures from these three agencies show further bigprepayment gains, as expected, traders look for thelower-coupon issues -- which are least vulnerable to earlyprepayments -- to continue performing strongly.   Today's session, as recommended by the Public SecuritiesAssociation, will end at 2 p.m. EST.</TEXT></DOC>